yeezus.pcb

Enum TaskManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<TaskManager>
      • yeezus.pcb.TaskManager
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<TaskManager>

    public enum TaskManager
extends java.lang.Enum<TaskManager>

    The Task Manager for the processes within the yeezus Operating System. This implementation is little more than a wrapper to control access to the PCBs it contains. To ensure that it remains a singleton, it is implemented as an Enum with a single instance.

    Processes are registered by the Loader at system startup using the addPCB(int, int, int, int, int, int, int) process. Once a process has been added, its PCB can be directly retrieved using the getPCB(int) method. A Job Queue that manages all un-run jobs on the system and a Ready Queue to keep track of which jobs have been loaded into RAM and are ready to go are both instantiated and maintained within this Task Manager. The Job Queue can be retrieved using the getJobQueue() method while the Ready Queue can be retrieved with the getReadyQueue() method.

    While all of the methods contained in this class are thread safe, the Lists that contain the Job Queue and the all of the PCBs are not, and they are returned as clones; any changes to them will not be reflected in the original, and they should be used for reading only. The Ready Queue, however, is thread safe, and can be edited outside of this class.

    Version:
    2.0
    Author:
    Mark Zeagler

      • getReadyQueue

        public java.util.Queue<PCB> getReadyQueue()

        Retrieves the Ready Queue for the system. The Ready Queue is a Queue of all PCBs associated with processes that are ready to run.

        For a list of all processes waiting to be run, use getJobQueue(). For a list of all PCBs of all processes, including those that have not yet completed, those that are currently running, and those that have already been completed, use getPCBs().

        Returns:
        A Queue of all PCBs associated with processes that are ready to be run. They should already be in order based on the current scheduling policy.

      • addPCB

        public void addPCB(int pid,
                   int startDiskInstructionAddress,
                   int instructionsLength,
                   int inputBufferLength,
                   int outputBufferLength,
                   int tempBufferLength,
                   int priority)
            throws DuplicateIDException
        Adds a PCB with the following attributes.
        Parameters:
        pid - The PCB ID of the new process.
        startDiskInstructionAddress - The start address of the Instructions on the disk.
        instructionsLength - The amount of Instructions on the disk.
        inputBufferLength - The length of the Input Buffer on the disk.
        outputBufferLength - The length of the Output Buffer on the disk.
        tempBufferLength - The length of the Temp Buffer on the disk.
        priority - The given priority of the process.
        Throws:
        DuplicateIDException

      • contains

        public boolean contains(int pid)

        Checks if this TaskManager contains a PCB with the given PID.

        NOTE: Since this instance is being used by multiple threads concurrently, there may be a change that occurs after this method has been run. It's best to attempt to retrieve the process directly, and handle any exceptions if it isn't there.

        Parameters:
        pid - The ID of the PCB to be checked.
        Returns:
        true if the TaskManager contains a PCB with the given PID, false if it doesn't.

      • getPCBs

        public java.util.List<PCB> getPCBs()

        Retrieves all of the PCBs that have run, are running, or will run on this system.

        For a list of all processes waiting to be run, use getJobQueue(). For PCBs of processes that are ready to be run, use getReadyQueue().

        NOTE: List is not synchronized, so the returned list is a clone of the original, not the original itself. Changes made to the cloned object will not be reflected in the original.

        Returns:
        A List of PCBs for all processes on the system.

      • getJobQueue

        public java.util.List<PCB> getJobQueue()

        Retrieves the Job Queue from the Task Manager.

        The Job Queue is the list of all processes that have not yet run. For a list of all PCBs of all processes, including those that have not yet completed, those that are currently running, and those that have already been completed, use getPCBs(). For PCBs of processes that are ready to be run, use getReadyQueue().

        NOTE: List is not synchronized, so the returned list is a clone of the original, not the original itself. Changes made to the cloned object will not be reflected in the original.

        Returns:
        A cloned List of all PCBs whose processes have not yet been completed within the system.
